			<p class="first_paragraph">
				Last week we looked at <em>The Silence of the Lambs</em> as a film that, in many ways, follows the traditional Hollywood approach to storytelling, creating a trait-motivated, tightly-cohesive cause-and-effect chain of events. One of the aspects of classical storytelling that we discussed last week was an emphasis on development of the plot over and above development of character. Typically, any character development that occurs in a classical film is done primarily to provide impetus to the plot development. 
			</p>
			<p>
				While it’s true that <em>The Silence of the Lambs</em> focuses most intently on developing the plot, one of the ways it breaks with classical storytelling is that it contains an unusual degree of “unnecessary” character development. While most films spend a certain amount of time developing an emotional attachment between the viewer and the main character, <em>Silence</em> does some unusual things in the way it treats Clarise Starling. Not only do we get backstory to motivate the character (information about Clarise’s family, her poor upbringing, her foster family--these things are not particularly unusual), but we also get visual flashbacks to moments from Clarise’s past. These <em>are</em> somewhat unusual in that they don’t impart any new information to us that we didn’t get through Clarise’s verbal retelling of her history. Demme puts a momentary hold on the narrative propulsion of the plot to spend a few moments projecting the viewer into Starling’s shoes and watching moments from her past play out, thus deepening the viewer’s emotional bond to Clarise. That deepening of the bond is really the only purpose that those flashbacks serve. They don’t contribute to the actual plot development in any way, and the “thriller” portion of the plot would be equally as effective if those shots were removed. 
			</p>
		</div>
	</div>
</div>
<div class="five_section_2">
