			<p>
				Another unusual aspect of this film is it’s incorporation of POV shots. We mentioned last week that classical storytelling typically uses objective narration, only rarely dipping into subjective POV for effect. That’s certainly true of this film, but Demme incorporates POV a bit more often than usual, and <em>when</em> he chooses to use POV is particularly interesting. It’s almost always used to place us into Clarise’s perspective. Take a look at the stills from various shots where instead of cutting back and forth between over-the-shoulder shots during a conversation, Demme chooses to have the characters look directly into the camera for Clarise’s perspective while Clarise looks slightly past the camera in a more traditional eyeline match shot. 
			</p>
